"""*Fig. 5(c): Poles and zeros of $S_0$ and $S_c$ plotted in the complex $\omega L$ plane. The green-white boundary depicts the $\mathcal{PT}$ phase transition of $S_0$. CPA point is clearly seen on the real axis where a pole and zero coincide*

In the figure, we see that before the transition point the poles (and the zeros resp.) have almost the same values of imaginary part as for the passive system. But, just at the transition of $S_0$ (again depicted by the green shaded area) there is an anticrossing of poles (and zeros) in the complex plane as half begin moving towards the real axis and the other half move away from the real axis. At $Re(\omega L)\approx 17$ we see that a pole and a zero coinciding on the real axis. This is called the Coherent Perfect Absorber (CPA) point. To understand why it is called so, we look at the eigenvalue equation of the scattering matrix.

$$S(\omega)\psi_n=s_n\psi_n$$

Here, $\psi_n$ represents two coherent light beams ($\omega$ real) incident from both sides of the heterostructure simultaneously. As we are at the CPA point, the eigenvalues vanish/diverge. Taking the specific case of the eigenvalue which vanishes, we have 

$$S(\omega)\psi_n=0$$

This implies that at the CPA point, for a particular mode, we do not have any scattered radiation. All of the incident radiation is perfectly absorbed. The other eigenvalue blowing up, tells us that for a particular mode, the heterostructure, emits laser radiation. The coincidence of the perfect absorption point and the lasing point is a property of 1D $\mathcal{PT}$ symmetric heterostructures that arises purely out of the symmetry properties of the $S$-matrix for such a structure.
"""

#plotting critical wL for phase transition boundaries AND CPA laser points
n_im = np.linspace(np.complex(2, 3.980*(10**-3)), np.complex(2, 4.3*(10**-3)), 1000)
wC = (np.log(2*n_im.real/n_im.imag))/(n_im.imag)
wCPA = wC + (1/n_im[i].imag)*np.log(5/3)

fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.set_xlabel("ω_c L (dimensionless)" )
ax.set_ylabel("Im[n]")
plt.ylim(bottom = 3.980*(10**-3), top = 4.3*(10**-3))
plt.xlim(left = 1720, right = 1730)
plt.title("Fig. Phase Transition Boundary and CPA laser points")
plt.plot(wC, n_im.imag ,'b')
plt.plot(wCPA, n_im.imag, 'r')

"""*Fig. 5(d): The red line depicts the CPA laser solutions while the blue lines depicts the phase boundary for a 1-D simple $\mathcal{PT}$-Symmetric heterostructure.*

## *6. Existence of ATRs in the asymptotic $\tau kL$ limit* 

For a general $\mathcal{PT}$symmetric system, nontrivial ATRs can exist in any of the phases of the S matrix ( whether symmetry is broken or not)
However, this is not the case for the simple heterostructure. 

In SH, ATRs disappear soon after the lasing threshold is passed in
the broken-symmetry phase. From equation (4.4), it is clear that this phase is reached in the large $\tau kL$ limit. For this case, $T \rightarrow 0$ asymptotically.

Consider
$$cot{\Delta} = \frac{1 + i\cot{(\Re\Delta)}\coth{(\Im\Delta)}}{i\coth{(\Im\Delta)} - \cot{(\Re\Delta)}}$$

But in the large $\tau kL$ limit, $coth{(\Im\Delta)} \rightarrow 1$

$$\implies \cot{\Delta} \rightarrow -i \\
\implies \cot{\Delta^*} \rightarrow i$$

Similiarly, we it is also simple to prove that:
$$ \sec{\Delta} \rightarrow 0 $$

To calculate $r_L$, we take take the reflection coefficient of the modified SH and take the limit that the passive layer is vanishingly small. That is, we apply $\sin{(\frac{2}{5}kL)} \rightarrow 0$ to equation (3.3)

$$ \implies r_L = \frac{\frac{1}{n} - n}{\frac{1}{n} + n + i2\cot{\Delta}}$$
\begin{equation}
  \implies r_L \rightarrow \frac{1-n}{1+n} \ \ \ \ \ \text{[asymptotically]}
\tag{6.1}
\end{equation}

By a similiar analysis, we get

\begin{equation}
r_R \rightarrow \frac{1+n^*}{1-n^*} \ \ \ \ \ \text{[asymptotically]}
\tag{6.2}
\end{equation} 
$$\text{Hence} \ \  R_RR_L \rightarrow 1 \implies T \rightarrow 0$$


Alternatively, we can calculate the transmission coefficient directly from the transmission matrix:

\begin{equation}
t = \frac{2ik e^{-ikL}\sec{\Delta}}{2i + (n + \frac{1}{n})\tan{\Delta}} \rightarrow 0 \ \ \ \ \ \ \text{since} \ \ \ \ \ \ \sec{\Delta} \rightarrow 0
\tag{6.3}
\end{equation} 

This proves that ATRs vanish as we can't have $T = 1$ when $T \rightarrow 0$
"""

#getting rL, rR and T through transfer matrix as before
n_SH = complex(2.0,0.2)
wL = np.linspace(20,50,1000)

delta = 0.5*n_SH*wL
alpha = ((abs(np.cos(delta))**2)/2) - (np.conj(n_SH)*(abs(np.sin(delta))**2))/(2*n_SH)
beta = (np.real(np.conj(n_SH)*np.sin(delta)*np.cos(np.conj(delta))))/(abs(n_SH)**2)
gamma = np.real(n_SH*np.sin(delta)*np.cos(np.conj(delta)))

tM1 = np.array([[(2*np.real(alpha) - complex(0,1)*(beta + gamma)), (2*np.imag(alpha) + (gamma - beta))*complex(0,1)], [(2*np.imag(alpha) - (gamma - beta))*complex(0,1), 2*np.real(alpha) + complex(0,1)*(beta + gamma)]])

rL = tM1[0][1]/tM1[1][1]
rR = -tM1[1][0]/tM1[1][1]
t = 1/tM1[1][1]

RL = abs(rL)**2
RR = abs(rR)**2
T = (abs(t)**2)


# defining the plots
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.set_xlabel("ωL (dimensionless)" )
ax.set_ylabel("T or R (dimensionless)")
plt.title("T, RR and RL plots")
plt.yscale('log')
plt.xlim(left = 20, right = 50)

plt.plot(wL, T,'r')
plt.plot(wL, RR,'g', linestyle = 'dashed')
plt.plot(wL, RL,'b', linestyle = 'dotted')

"""*Fig. 6(a): Plots of T, R_R and R_L for a simple heterojuction for large frequencies. The transmittance is tending to 0 making ATRs impossible.*

However, this is not true in general. More complicated structures can have ATRs even in the large $\tau kL$ limit. For example, consider the modified simple heterojunction. First we prove that the passive layer in between can undergo transmission resonances. Normally, this won't lead to an ATR of the whole structure, but in the large $\tau kL$ limit, it does.

The passive layer can be treated as a homogenous block of refractive index n such that $Im(n) = 0$. A transmission resonance here must satisfy the same constraint:
$$ B = \left ( \left ( 1 - \frac{n_r}{n_l} \right )\cos{\Delta} + i \left ( \frac{n}{n_l} - \frac{n_r}{n} \right )\sin{\Delta} \right )C = 0 \tag{3.2}$$
Taking note that for this structure, $n_r = n_l*$, we get:
$$ \left ( \frac{n_l*}{n_l} - 1 \right )\cos{\Delta} = i \left ( \frac{n}{n_l} - \frac{n_l*}{n} \right )\sin{\Delta}  \implies \Delta =  \arctan{\left( \frac{2Im(n_l)n}{|n_l|^2 - n^2} \right)} \tag{6.5}$$
For small frequecies, this doesn't lead to ATRs because there are multiple interferences taking place in the gain and loss blocks. for large frequencies, the absorption and amplification is strong enough to suppress the interference and that leads to ATRs periodically in the large $ \tau kL$ limit. Since the structure cannot have trivial ATRs as proved before, all these ATRs are non-trivial. This analysis is picturised in Fig 6(b)

The same analysis works if we extend the gain and loss layers on each side of the passive layer to infinity. This leads to $\tau kL \rightarrow \infty$ and hence the solutions of (3.2) lead to ATRs. This is shown in Fig. 6(c)
"""

#Similar to the Gain-Passive-Loss system code in Section-2
wL = np.linspace(80,100,10000001)
wL2 = np.linspace(92.345,92.35,1001)

def pl(w, lt, rt):
  nL = complex(2.0,0.2)
  dL = 0.3*nL*w

  nG = complex(2.0,-0.2)
  dG = 0.3*nG*w

  n = 2
  d = 0.4*n*w

  M3 = np.array([[ np.cos(dL) , (np.sin(dL))/(nL*w) ],
                [ -1*np.sin(dL)*nL*w  , np.cos(dL) ]])

  M2 = np.array([[ np.cos(d) , (np.sin(d))/(n*w) ],
                [ -1*np.sin(d)*n*w  , np.cos(d) ]])

  M1 = np.array([[ np.cos(dG) , (np.sin(dG))/(nG*w) ],
                [ -1*np.sin(dG)*nG*w  , np.cos(dG) ]])

  M12 = np.einsum('ijk,jlk->ilk',M1,M2)
  ML = np.einsum('ijk,jlk->ilk',M12,M3)

  rL = ((ML[1][0]) + (w*w*ML[0][1]) + (complex(0,1)*w*(ML[1][1] - ML[0][0])))/((-1*ML[1][0]) + (w*w*ML[0][1]) + (complex(0,1)*w*(ML[1][1] + ML[0][0])))
  t = (2*complex(0,1)*w*np.exp(complex(0,1)*(-1)*w))/((-1*ML[1][0]) + (w*w*ML[0][1]) + (complex(0,1)*w*(ML[1][1] + ML[0][0])))

  RL = (abs(rL)**2)
  T = (abs(t)**2)
  RR = ((1-T)**2)/RL


  fig, ax = plt.subplots()
  ax.set_xlabel("ωL (dimensionless)" )
  ax.set_ylabel("Magnitude in powers of 10")
  plt.title("T, RR, RL for modified Sh")
  plt.yscale("log")
  plt.xlim(lt, rt)
  plt.plot(w, T,'r')
  plt.plot(w, RR,'g', linestyle = 'dashed')
  plt.plot(w, RL,'b', linestyle = 'dotted')
pl(wL, 80, 100)
pl(wL2, 92.345, 92.35)
